export function getStaticPaths() {
  const questions = [
    {
      slug: "how-much-does-kitchen-installation-cost",
      title: "How Much Does Kitchen Installation Cost?",
      metaDescription: "Kitchen installation in the UK typically costs £1,800–£7,500. Discover what affects your price, cost per unit, labour rates and why a survey gets you an accurate quote.",
      answer: "Kitchen installation typically costs £1,800–£7,500 depending on kitchen size, complexity and retailer. A small kitchen (8–12 units) starts from around £1,800; a large kitchen (21+ units) can reach £7,500 or more. A survey from Install My Kitchen costs £195 and is credited back on booking.",
      takeaways: ["Small kitchens (8–12 units) typically cost £1,800–£2,800", "Medium kitchens (13–20 units) typically cost £2,800–£4,200", "Large kitchens (21+ units) typically cost £4,200–£7,500", "The £195 survey fee is credited back against your installation balance"],
      body: `<h2>Kitchen Installation Cost by Size</h2><p>The most significant factor affecting installation cost is kitchen size — specifically the number of units and the number of days required to fit them. As a general guide across Coventry and Warwickshire:</p><ul><li><strong>Small kitchen (8–12 units):</strong> 3–4 days, typically £1,800–£2,800</li><li><strong>Medium kitchen (13–20 units):</strong> 4–6 days, typically £2,800–£4,200</li><li><strong>Large kitchen (21+ units):</strong> 6–10 days, typically £4,200–£7,500</li></ul><h2>What Affects the Final Price?</h2><p>Beyond size, several factors push costs higher or lower. Complex corner units, tall larder units, and island installations all take additional time. German flat-pack brands such as IKEA require full on-site assembly, which typically adds one to two days compared to pre-assembled units from retailers such as Wren or Howdens.</p><p>Worktop type also matters. Laminate worktops can be cut and fitted directly; stone worktops (quartz, granite) require separate templating by a specialist, co-ordinated around the installation programme. Appliance count is a further variable — a kitchen with six integrated appliances takes meaningfully longer to fit than one with two.</p><h2>Labour Rate</h2><p>Install My Kitchen charges approximately £350 per day for kitchen installation labour in Coventry and Warwickshire. This rate covers the full installation service including all cabinet assembly, levelling, worktops, doors, drawers, handles, plinths, cornices and snagging. It does not include first or second-fix plumbing, electrical work or gas connections, which should be arranged with qualified tradespeople separately.</p><h2>Why a Survey Gives You an Accurate Price</h2><p>Online cost guides — including this one — can only give you a range. The only way to get a precise price for your specific kitchen, in your specific home, is through a pre-installation survey. Our survey costs £195 and is credited back in full when you confirm your installation date and pay your deposit. It typically pays for itself many times over in avoided surprises.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "How much does kitchen installation cost per unit?", a: "Typically £120–£280 per unit depending on cabinet type and complexity. Corner units and tall larder units take longer and cost more per unit than standard base or wall units." },
        { q: "Does the retailer affect installation cost?", a: "Yes. Flat-pack brands such as IKEA require full assembly on site, adding time and cost. Pre-assembled rigid units from Wren, Howdens or Magnet are faster to install at standard rates." },
        { q: "Is the survey fee refundable?", a: "The survey fee of £195 is not refundable if you choose not to proceed. However, it is credited in full against your installation balance when you confirm your date and pay your deposit." },
        { q: "Are there any hidden costs?", a: "Our quotes are fixed and comprehensive for the agreed scope. Additional costs can arise if the room requires unforeseen remedial work — such as out-of-plumb walls requiring specialist scribing — which is why the survey is so important." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "how-long-does-kitchen-installation-take",
      title: "How Long Does Kitchen Installation Take?",
      metaDescription: "A small kitchen takes 3–4 days to install; a large kitchen 6–10 days. Find out what affects installation timescales and how to plan your project.",
      answer: "A small kitchen typically takes 3–4 days to install; a medium kitchen 4–6 days; a large kitchen 6–10 days. This assumes all deliveries are on site, services are prepared, and no structural changes are needed.",
      takeaways: ["Small kitchens (8–12 units): 3–4 installation days", "Medium kitchens (13–20 units): 4–6 installation days", "Large kitchens (21+ units): 6–10 installation days", "IKEA flat-pack kitchens add 1–2 extra days for assembly"],
      body: `<h2>Day-by-Day Installation Timeline</h2><p>For a typical medium kitchen installation, the programme broadly follows this sequence:</p><ul><li><strong>Day 1:</strong> Delivery check, protection of floors and adjacent rooms, strip-out of existing kitchen, first base units installed and levelled</li><li><strong>Day 2–3:</strong> Remaining carcasses, wall units, any tall units or larder towers</li><li><strong>Day 3–4:</strong> Worktop templating (stone) or fitting (laminate), sink cutout</li><li><strong>Day 4–5:</strong> Doors, drawers, handles, plinths, cornices, fillers</li><li><strong>Day 5–6:</strong> Appliances, second-fix plumbing and electrics (by others), final snagging and handover</li></ul><h2>What Makes a Kitchen Take Longer?</h2><p>Several factors extend the programme beyond the base estimate. IKEA kitchens are supplied flat-pack and require full assembly on site before installation can begin — this typically adds a full day or more. Kitchens with a high number of integrated appliances take longer at the fitting stage. Island units, peninsulas, and open shelving all add time.</p><p>Room conditions also matter. An out-of-level floor requires more careful packing and adjustment at the base unit stage. Very uneven or out-of-plumb walls require scribing of filler panels, which is time-consuming work. Our survey identifies all of these factors before installation begins so that your quote and programme reflect the reality of your room.</p><h2>What Must Be Ready Before We Start?</h2><p>To avoid delays, first-fix plumbing, electrical and gas work must be complete before installation day. This means water supply and waste pipes should be in their final positions, electrical sockets and switches roughed in, and gas connections capped in their correct locations. Our survey will confirm exactly what needs to be ready and provide a services drawing if required.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "Can you install a kitchen in one day?", a: "A very small galley kitchen with 6–8 units could theoretically be installed in a single long day, but this is uncommon. Most installations require a minimum of 2–3 days to achieve a quality result." },
        { q: "Do you work weekends?", a: "We primarily work Monday to Saturday. Weekend availability depends on scheduling — please discuss your preferred dates when booking your survey." },
        { q: "What happens if a part is missing on installation day?", a: "Our pre-installation survey checks your delivery against your kitchen plan. Missing parts identified before installation day can be ordered in advance. Parts discovered on the day may cause a delay — the survey is the best way to avoid this." },
        { q: "How long does worktop fitting take?", a: "Laminate worktops can typically be fitted in half a day. Stone worktops (quartz, granite) require a separate templating visit 1–2 days before fitting, then a return visit of half to one day for installation." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "do-i-need-a-survey-before-kitchen-installation",
      title: "Do I Need a Survey Before Kitchen Installation?",
      metaDescription: "A pre-installation survey is strongly recommended. It checks your room against the plan, identifies risks, and gives you an accurate fixed quote. Survey £195, credited back.",
      answer: "A pre-installation survey is strongly recommended. It checks that your room matches your kitchen plan, confirms services are correctly positioned, identifies any risks, and enables an accurate fixed quote. Install My Kitchen's survey costs £195 and is credited back against your installation balance on booking.",
      takeaways: ["A survey catches problems before they become expensive on-site surprises", "Our survey checks room dimensions, services, levels, walls, access and appliances", "The £195 fee is credited back in full when you book your installation", "Skipping a survey risks delays, additional costs and a poor finish"],
      body: `<h2>What Does a Kitchen Installation Survey Cover?</h2><p>Our pre-installation survey is a thorough assessment of your home and your kitchen plan conducted by an experienced surveyor. It covers:</p><ul><li><strong>Room dimensions vs plan:</strong> We measure every dimension of your room with laser equipment and compare it against your kitchen designer's drawing. Discrepancies are common and can require changes to the kitchen plan.</li><li><strong>Service positions:</strong> Water supply and waste, electrical sockets and circuits, and gas connections are all checked against the planned positions for your appliances and sink.</li><li><strong>Floor levels:</strong> An unlevel floor requires careful packing during installation. We assess the extent of any variation and factor this into the programme.</li><li><strong>Wall condition:</strong> Out-of-plumb or uneven walls require scribing of filler panels and end panels. Walls with surface issues may need remedial work before installation.</li><li><strong>Access routes:</strong> We check that units, particularly tall larder units and large appliances, can be brought through your doors, hallway and staircase if necessary.</li><li><strong>Appliance positions:</strong> We confirm that all appliances fit the specified spaces and that services are in the correct position.</li></ul><h2>What Happens Without a Survey?</h2><p>Installations that proceed without a survey frequently encounter problems that could have been avoided. The most common are room dimensions that do not match the plan, resulting in units that do not fit; service positions that are in the wrong location for the planned appliances; and floor or wall conditions that require additional work, extending the programme and adding cost.</p><h2>The Survey Fee</h2><p>Our survey costs £195. This is credited in full against your installation balance when you confirm your date and pay your deposit. If you choose not to proceed after the survey, the fee is retained. For the peace of mind and accuracy a survey provides, it represents exceptional value.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "How long does the survey take?", a: "Typically 45 minutes to 1.5 hours depending on kitchen complexity. We ask that someone over 18 is present throughout." },
        { q: "What do I need to have ready for the survey?", a: "Your kitchen plan or designer's drawings, any appliance specifications, and access to the room including under-floor areas if relevant. The more information you have to hand, the more accurate the survey outcome." },
        { q: "Can I get a quote without a survey?", a: "We can provide a broad estimate based on kitchen size and retailer. However, a fixed, accurate quote requires a survey visit. We strongly recommend a survey before committing to any installation." },
        { q: "What if the survey reveals a problem?", a: "We will explain the issue clearly, advise on the most cost-effective solution, and adjust the installation quote accordingly. In most cases, problems identified at survey stage are straightforward to resolve." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "what-is-a-dry-fit-kitchen",
      title: "What Is a Dry Fit Kitchen?",
      metaDescription: "A dry fit is when kitchen units are positioned without final fixing to verify layout before permanent installation. Learn when it's used and how it protects your project.",
      answer: "A dry fit (also called a trial fit) is when kitchen units are assembled and positioned without final fixing, allowing positions to be verified before permanent installation. It is particularly useful where walls are uneven, ceilings are low, or appliance positions need confirming.",
      takeaways: ["A dry fit positions units without final fixing to verify layout", "Useful for complex layouts, uneven rooms and appliance positioning", "Adds time to the programme but can prevent costly mistakes", "Our survey identifies whether a dry fit is recommended for your project"],
      body: `<h2>What Is a Dry Fit?</h2><p>A dry fit — sometimes called a trial fit or a false fit — is a stage in a kitchen installation where units are assembled and placed in their intended positions without being permanently fixed to walls or floors. This allows the fitter and the client to verify that the layout works as planned before any irreversible fixing takes place.</p><h2>When Is a Dry Fit Used?</h2><p>A dry fit is most commonly used in kitchens where the room presents particular challenges. These include rooms with significantly uneven floors or out-of-plumb walls, where the impact of levelling on the final appearance needs to be assessed before fixing. It is also valuable in open-plan spaces where the visual relationship between the kitchen and the rest of the room is important, and where the client wishes to walk around the space before committing.</p><p>For kitchens with complex corner arrangements, island units, or large appliances that need to slot into tight spaces, a dry fit confirms that everything fits and that there is adequate clearance for doors to open and drawers to extend fully.</p><h2>Does a Dry Fit Add Cost?</h2><p>A dry fit adds time to the installation programme — typically half a day to a full day — and this is reflected in the installation quote if one is recommended following the survey. In most cases, the additional cost is modest relative to the risk it mitigates. For standard kitchen layouts in rooms without significant challenges, a full dry fit is often unnecessary.</p><h2>Our Approach</h2><p>At Install My Kitchen, our surveyor will assess your room and kitchen plan and advise whether a dry fit stage is recommended. We do not charge for a dry fit as a default — we only include it where it genuinely adds value to the project. This recommendation is part of what makes our pre-installation survey worthwhile.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "Is a dry fit the same as a trial fit?", a: "Yes, the terms are interchangeable. Both refer to positioning units without permanent fixing to verify layout before installation is completed." },
        { q: "Do all kitchen fitters offer a dry fit?", a: "Not all fitters offer or recommend a dry fit as standard. Whether it is appropriate depends on the room and kitchen. Our surveyor will advise whether it is needed for your project." },
        { q: "Can I request a dry fit even if my room is straightforward?", a: "Yes. If you would like the reassurance of seeing the kitchen positioned before fixing, we can accommodate this. Please raise it at your survey appointment." },
        { q: "Does a dry fit affect the installation warranty?", a: "No. The dry fit is simply a stage within the same installation process. The workmanship warranty covers the completed installation regardless of whether a dry fit stage was included." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "can-you-fit-an-ikea-kitchen",
      title: "Can You Fit an IKEA Kitchen?",
      metaDescription: "Yes — Install My Kitchen installs IKEA kitchens across Coventry and Warwickshire. Learn about IKEA flat-pack assembly, timescales and what to expect.",
      answer: "Yes. Install My Kitchen installs IKEA kitchens across Coventry and Warwickshire. IKEA kitchens are flat-pack and require careful assembly before installation, which typically adds one to two days compared to pre-assembled units. We are independent of IKEA and not affiliated with them.",
      takeaways: ["We install IKEA kitchens across Coventry and Warwickshire", "IKEA flat-pack requires full on-site assembly — allow 1–2 extra days", "We are completely independent of IKEA and not affiliated with them", "A survey is recommended to check your IKEA plan against your room"],
      body: `<h2>Installing an IKEA Kitchen</h2><p>IKEA kitchens are one of the most popular choices in the UK, offering a wide range of styles and finishes at accessible price points. The METOD system — IKEA's current kitchen range — is a well-designed modular system that an experienced independent fitter can install to a high standard.</p><h2>The Flat-Pack Difference</h2><p>The key difference between an IKEA kitchen and kitchens from retailers such as Wren, Howdens or Magnet is that IKEA units are supplied flat-pack and must be fully assembled on site before installation. This is a significant additional task. Each carcass must be assembled from its components before it can be levelled and fixed in position. For a medium-sized IKEA kitchen, this assembly process typically adds one to two full days to the installation programme compared to a pre-assembled kitchen of the same size.</p><p>This additional time is reflected in our installation quotes for IKEA kitchens. We do not rush the assembly stage — each carcass is assembled correctly, with all clips and fixings properly engaged, before it is installed. Poorly assembled IKEA carcasses are a common cause of door alignment problems and drawer failures later.</p><h2>Checking Your IKEA Order</h2><p>Before installation day, we strongly recommend checking your IKEA delivery carefully against your order. IKEA kitchens are ordered as individual components, and missing parts — a single hinge pack, a drawer front in the wrong size, or a missing worktop bracket — can delay installation. Our pre-installation survey includes a review of your IKEA plan to identify any obvious gaps or conflicts before delivery.</p><h2>Affiliation Disclaimer</h2><p>Install My Kitchen is an independent kitchen installation service and is not affiliated with, endorsed by, or an official partner of IKEA. We install kitchens purchased from IKEA by our clients.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "How much does IKEA kitchen installation cost?", a: "IKEA kitchen installation typically costs slightly more than equivalent pre-assembled kitchens due to the assembly time required. A medium IKEA kitchen typically costs £3,200–£4,800 to install, depending on size and complexity." },
        { q: "Do you supply IKEA parts or just install?", a: "We install kitchens purchased by our clients from IKEA. We do not supply IKEA components. All units, doors, handles and accessories should be ordered and delivered before the installation date." },
        { q: "Can you install PAX wardrobes or other IKEA furniture?", a: "Our primary service is kitchen installation. We do not routinely install IKEA wardrobe systems or other IKEA furniture. Please contact us if you have a specific requirement." },
        { q: "What IKEA kitchen ranges do you install?", a: "We install the current METOD system in all door styles and finishes. We are familiar with AXSTAD, VOXTORP, KUNGSBACKA, BODBYN, KALLARP and all other current METOD door families." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "can-you-fit-a-wren-kitchen",
      title: "Can You Fit a Wren Kitchen?",
      metaDescription: "Yes — Install My Kitchen installs Wren kitchens independently across Coventry and Warwickshire. We are not affiliated with Wren Kitchens.",
      answer: "Yes. Install My Kitchen installs Wren kitchens across Coventry and Warwickshire. Wren delivers kitchens fully assembled to your door, which makes the installation process efficient. We are an independent service and are not affiliated with Wren Kitchens.",
      takeaways: ["We install Wren kitchens independently across Coventry and Warwickshire", "Wren delivers fully assembled rigid units — efficient to install", "We are not affiliated with Wren — we work for you, not them", "A survey ensures your Wren design works in your actual room"],
      body: `<h2>Installing a Wren Kitchen</h2><p>Wren Kitchens is one of the UK's most popular kitchen retailers, known for its wide range of styles at competitive prices. Wren kitchens are supplied as rigid, pre-assembled units delivered directly to your home — a format that makes them straightforward and efficient for an experienced independent fitter to install.</p><h2>What to Expect</h2><p>Wren delivers your kitchen in a single scheduled delivery, typically the day before or on the morning of installation. Units arrive fully assembled — the carcass is complete and only needs to be levelled, positioned, and fixed in place. This distinguishes Wren kitchens from flat-pack brands such as IKEA and means that a medium Wren kitchen can typically be installed in 4–5 days rather than the 5–7 days a comparable IKEA kitchen might require.</p><p>Wren kitchens include a comprehensive range of accessories — soft-close hinges, drawer runners, pull-out storage systems, and integrated lighting — all of which our fitters are experienced in fitting and adjusting. The snagging stage of a Wren kitchen typically focuses on door and drawer alignment, handle positioning, and the fit of plinths and cornices.</p><h2>Checking Your Wren Delivery</h2><p>Before your installation date, check your Wren delivery carefully against the delivery note. Wren has a reputation for resolving missing or damaged components promptly, but any issues are better identified before installation day. Our pre-installation survey includes a review of your Wren design drawings to confirm the plan works in your room.</p><h2>Affiliation Disclaimer</h2><p>Install My Kitchen is an independent kitchen installation service and is not affiliated with, endorsed by, or an official partner of Wren Kitchens. We install kitchens purchased from Wren by our clients.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "Does Wren offer their own installation service?", a: "Yes, Wren offers an installation service through their network of approved fitters. However, you are not required to use it. Many customers choose independent fitters for flexibility, pricing, or a more personal service." },
        { q: "Is Wren a good kitchen brand?", a: "Wren offers a wide range at various price points. Their rigid unit construction is a positive feature for installation quality. As with any retailer, the finish of the installed kitchen depends significantly on the quality of the fitter." },
        { q: "How long does a Wren kitchen take to install?", a: "A medium Wren kitchen (13–20 units) typically takes 4–6 days to install. Large or complex kitchens may take longer. Our survey provides a precise programme for your kitchen." },
        { q: "What if units are damaged on delivery?", a: "Report any damage to Wren on delivery and before installation begins. Wren's customer service team handles replacement of damaged components. Do not allow installation to begin on damaged units." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "can-you-fit-a-howdens-kitchen",
      title: "Can You Fit a Howdens Kitchen?",
      metaDescription: "Yes — we install Howdens kitchens independently across Coventry and Warwickshire. Trade-quality rigid units, efficient installation. Not affiliated with Howdens.",
      answer: "Yes. We install Howdens kitchens across Coventry and Warwickshire. Howdens supplies through trade accounts and units are trade quality and rigid. We are independent of Howdens and not affiliated with them.",
      takeaways: ["We install Howdens kitchens independently across Coventry and Warwickshire", "Howdens supplies trade-quality rigid units through trade accounts", "We are not affiliated with Howdens — we work exclusively for you", "Howdens units are efficient to install due to their rigid construction"],
      body: `<h2>Installing a Howdens Kitchen</h2><p>Howdens Joinery is the UK's largest kitchen supplier, selling exclusively through trade accounts to builders, developers, and kitchen fitters. Their range — which spans entry-level to premium — is supplied as rigid, pre-assembled units of consistent trade quality. Howdens kitchens are among the most efficient to install due to their well-engineered carcass system and consistent tolerances.</p><h2>The Howdens Trade Model</h2><p>Unlike consumer retailers such as Wren or IKEA, Howdens does not sell directly to homeowners. Units are ordered through a trade account and collected from a local Howdens depot. If you have purchased a Howdens kitchen through a builder or directly through a trade account, we can install it for you as an independent service.</p><h2>What to Expect</h2><p>Howdens units are supplied rigid and pre-assembled. The carcass system is well-designed with clear fixing points and consistent dimensions, which makes the installation process efficient. Howdens accessories — including their Lift & Slide storage systems, Blum soft-close hinges, and integrated lighting — are straightforward to fit. The range of door styles is broad, from simple slab doors to detailed in-frame styles, and our fitters are experienced across the full Howdens range.</p><h2>Affiliation Disclaimer</h2><p>Install My Kitchen is an independent kitchen installation service and is not affiliated with, endorsed by, or an official partner of Howdens Joinery. We install kitchens purchased from Howdens by our clients.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "Can I buy a Howdens kitchen without a trade account?", a: "Howdens sells through trade accounts only. However, a builder, developer, or fitter with a trade account can purchase on your behalf. Some independent fitters, including ourselves, can assist clients in sourcing Howdens kitchens." },
        { q: "How does Howdens delivery work?", a: "Howdens units are typically collected from the local depot by the fitter or delivered to site. Delivery is arranged separately from the installation programme. Our survey will confirm delivery logistics for your project." },
        { q: "Is Howdens a good quality kitchen?", a: "Howdens offers a broad range with consistent quality at each price point. Their trade-focused construction is generally robust and well-suited to professional installation. The result depends significantly on the quality and care of the fitter." },
        { q: "How long does a Howdens kitchen installation take?", a: "A medium Howdens kitchen typically takes 4–5 days. The efficient rigid unit system means Howdens installations are often at the faster end of the range for a given kitchen size." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "can-you-fit-a-magnet-kitchen",
      title: "Can You Fit a Magnet Kitchen?",
      metaDescription: "Yes — we install Magnet kitchens independently across Coventry and Warwickshire. Expert fitting for all Magnet ranges. Not affiliated with Magnet.",
      answer: "Yes. We install Magnet kitchens independently across Coventry and Warwickshire. Magnet kitchens are rigid and well-finished. We are an independent service and not affiliated with Magnet.",
      takeaways: ["We install all Magnet kitchen ranges independently", "Magnet supplies rigid pre-assembled units — efficient to install", "We are not affiliated with Magnet or Magnet Trade", "A survey confirms your Magnet design works in your room"],
      body: `<h2>Installing a Magnet Kitchen</h2><p>Magnet Kitchens is one of the UK's longest-established kitchen retailers, offering a broad range from entry-level fitted kitchens through to premium in-frame and painted styles. Magnet kitchens are supplied as rigid, pre-assembled units and are straightforward for an experienced independent fitter to install.</p><h2>Magnet and Magnet Trade</h2><p>Magnet operates two routes to market: the consumer-facing Magnet brand, sold through showrooms, and Magnet Trade, a trade supply operation similar to Howdens. Both supply the same quality of rigid carcass construction. Whether your kitchen was purchased through a Magnet showroom or through a Magnet Trade account, we can install it independently.</p><h2>What to Expect</h2><p>Magnet kitchens span a wide range of styles, from simple modern handleless kitchens to detailed traditional painted and in-frame designs. The installation complexity varies accordingly — a handleless kitchen with integrated appliances is a more demanding install than a standard shaker kitchen, but both are well within our capability. Our survey will assess the specific requirements of your Magnet kitchen and provide an accurate programme and quote.</p><h2>Affiliation Disclaimer</h2><p>Install My Kitchen is an independent kitchen installation service and is not affiliated with, endorsed by, or an official partner of Magnet Kitchens or Magnet Trade. We install kitchens purchased from Magnet by our clients.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "Does Magnet offer their own installation?", a: "Yes, Magnet offers installation through their own service. You are not required to use it. Independent fitters often offer more flexible scheduling and competitive pricing." },
        { q: "What Magnet ranges do you install?", a: "We install all Magnet ranges including Magnet Trade, standard consumer ranges, and premium painted and in-frame styles. Our surveyor will review your specific kitchen plan at the survey visit." },
        { q: "How long does a Magnet kitchen take to install?", a: "A medium Magnet kitchen (13–20 units) typically takes 4–6 days. Premium in-frame and painted styles may take longer due to the precision required." },
        { q: "Can you install Magnet Trade kitchens?", a: "Yes. Magnet Trade kitchens use the same rigid carcass system as the consumer range. We install both." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "what-is-included-in-kitchen-installation",
      title: "What Is Included in Kitchen Installation?",
      metaDescription: "Kitchen installation includes cabinets, worktops, doors, drawers, handles, plinths, appliances and snagging. Find out exactly what's included and what isn't.",
      answer: "Our kitchen installation includes cabinet assembly and fitting, worktops, doors, drawers, panels, trims, plinths, cornices, pelmets, fillers, appliance and sink fitting, handles, and final adjustments and snagging. Optional extras include flooring, tiling and decorating.",
      takeaways: ["Cabinets, worktops, doors, drawers and all trims are included", "Appliance and sink fitting is included", "First and second-fix plumbing, electrical and gas work are not included", "Optional: flooring, tiling, decorating"],
      body: `<h2>What's Included in Our Kitchen Installation Service</h2><p>Our standard kitchen installation service covers every element of fitting the kitchen itself. In full, this includes:</p><ul><li><strong>Cabinet assembly and installation:</strong> All base units, wall units, tall/larder units, corner units — assembled where required, levelled and fixed to walls and floors</li><li><strong>Worktop supply and fitting:</strong> Laminate worktops supplied and fitted; stone worktops (quartz, granite, solid surface) co-ordinated with your specialist supplier</li><li><strong>Doors and drawers:</strong> All kitchen doors and drawer fronts fitted, hinges adjusted, soft-close mechanisms calibrated</li><li><strong>Decorative panels and end panels:</strong> All visible side panels, larder panels, and island panels fitted and finished</li><li><strong>Trims and finishing elements:</strong> Plinths, cornices, light pelmets, cover fillers, glazing bead, cornice lighting — all fitted</li><li><strong>Handles and ironmongery:</strong> All handles, knobs and bar pulls fitted with template jigs for consistent positioning</li><li><strong>Appliance and sink fitting:</strong> All integrated appliances positioned and fitted; sink bowls fitted into worktop apertures</li><li><strong>Snagging and handover:</strong> Full final check of all doors, drawers, and elements before handover</li></ul><h2>What's Not Included</h2><p>First and second-fix plumbing, electrical work, and gas connections are not included in our installation service. Due to high demand and fast-filling slots, we recommend arranging your own qualified electricians, plumbers and gas engineers before your installation date wherever possible. This approach gives you control over your own tradespeople and ensures they are available when needed.</p><h2>Optional Extras</h2><p>Flooring, wall tiling, and decorating are available as optional additions to the installation service, subject to availability. These are quoted separately. Please discuss your requirements at the survey appointment.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "Do you supply the kitchen units?", a: "No. Our service is installation only. You purchase your kitchen from your chosen retailer — Wren, Howdens, Magnet, IKEA or any other — and we install it." },
        { q: "Do you remove the old kitchen?", a: "Strip-out of the existing kitchen is not included in our standard service but can be arranged. Please discuss this at your survey appointment." },
        { q: "Do you supply worktops?", a: "We supply and fit laminate worktops. For stone worktops (quartz, granite, Dekton), we work with your chosen stone supplier and co-ordinate the templating and fitting appointment." },
        { q: "Are soft-close hinges and drawer runners included?", a: "Yes, if they are supplied with your kitchen units. We fit whatever hardware is supplied with the units and calibrate it correctly during installation." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "do-i-need-a-plumber-for-kitchen-installation",
      title: "Do I Need a Plumber for Kitchen Installation?",
      metaDescription: "Yes — a qualified plumber handles water connections for your kitchen. Learn what first and second-fix plumbing involves and how to co-ordinate trades.",
      answer: "Yes — you will need a qualified plumber for first and second-fix plumbing (water supply and waste connections). Due to high demand, we recommend arranging your own qualified plumbers, electricians and gas engineers before your installation date wherever possible.",
      takeaways: ["A qualified plumber is needed for water supply and waste connections", "First fix (pipe positions) must be done before installation", "Second fix (connecting sink/dishwasher) happens after units are in", "Arrange your plumber before booking your installation date"],
      body: `<h2>Plumbing and Kitchen Installation</h2><p>Kitchen installation involves two distinct plumbing stages — first fix and second fix — and both require a qualified plumber. Understanding the difference helps you plan your project effectively.</p><h2>First Fix Plumbing</h2><p>First fix plumbing covers all the pipework that needs to be in place before kitchen installation begins. This includes routing the cold water supply to the sink position, routing the waste pipe to the sink and dishwasher positions, and capping or re-routing any existing pipes that no longer align with the new layout. First fix must be complete — with pipes in their final positions — before we begin installing units.</p><h2>Second Fix Plumbing</h2><p>Second fix plumbing connects the appliances and sink once the units and worktop are in place. This includes connecting the tap to the water supply, connecting the waste to the sink bowl and dishwasher, and connecting any plumbed appliances such as a washing machine or fridge with water dispenser. Second fix typically takes half a day and is scheduled towards the end of the kitchen installation programme, after the worktop is fitted.</p><h2>Electrical and Gas</h2><p>In addition to plumbing, most kitchens require an electrician for second fix electrical work — connecting hardwired appliances such as ovens and hobs, fitting sockets, and testing circuits. If your kitchen includes a gas hob or range cooker, a Gas Safe registered engineer is required. Due to high demand and fast-filling slots, we recommend arranging all of these tradespeople well in advance of your installation date.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "Do you do any plumbing work?", a: "Our installation service does not include plumbing. We work alongside your plumber to co-ordinate the first and second fix stages within the installation programme." },
        { q: "When should I book my plumber?", a: "Book your plumber as early as possible — ideally at the same time you book your installation date. Good plumbers are in high demand. Your installation survey will confirm the exact programme so you can schedule trades accordingly." },
        { q: "Do I need a Gas Safe engineer for an electric hob?", a: "No — Gas Safe registration is only required for gas appliances (hobs, range cookers, gas ovens). An electric hob requires an electrician for a hardwired connection." },
        { q: "What if my plumber runs over on first fix?", a: "If first fix is not complete when we are scheduled to start, we may not be able to begin installation. We will work with you to reschedule as early as possible, but delays to trades are a leading cause of installation delays. The survey helps you plan all trades accurately." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "how-do-i-prepare-for-kitchen-installation",
      title: "How Do I Prepare for Kitchen Installation?",
      metaDescription: "Prepare for kitchen installation by confirming delivery, booking trades, clearing the room and checking services are ready. Full checklist from Install My Kitchen.",
      answer: "Before your installation date: confirm your kitchen delivery is complete and undamaged, ensure first-fix plumbing, electrical and gas work is done, clear the room and access routes, and confirm worktop measurements. Our survey covers all of this in advance.",
      takeaways: ["Check your full delivery before installation day", "First-fix plumbing and electrical must be complete before we start", "Clear the room and all access routes on installation day", "Stone worktop templating must happen before the installation completes"],
      body: `<h2>Complete Pre-Installation Checklist</h2><h2>4–6 Weeks Before</h2><ul><li>Book your plumber, electrician and gas engineer (if applicable) — good tradespeople get booked up quickly</li><li>Confirm your kitchen delivery date with your retailer — it should arrive 1–2 days before installation</li><li>If you have stone worktops, confirm the templating date with your worktop supplier</li><li>Arrange temporary kitchen facilities (kettle, microwave, small fridge) — you may be without a kitchen for several days</li></ul><h2>1–2 Weeks Before</h2><ul><li>Confirm your delivery contents against your order — report any discrepancies to your retailer immediately</li><li>Confirm that your plumber has scheduled first fix to be complete before the installation start date</li><li>Check that your electrician has scheduled first fix electrical work (new sockets, circuit for oven/hob)</li><li>Empty all cupboards and clear the kitchen area completely</li></ul><h2>The Day Before</h2><ul><li>Protect floors in hallways and adjacent rooms with dust sheets or hardboard</li><li>Confirm delivery has arrived and check for any damaged units — report damage to retailer before installation begins</li><li>Ensure parking is available for our van</li></ul><h2>Installation Day</h2><ul><li>Ensure water, electricity and gas can be turned off at the mains if required</li><li>Keep children and pets away from the work area</li><li>Be available (or have a responsible adult present) throughout the day</li></ul>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "Do I need to be at home during the kitchen installation?", a: "You do not need to be present throughout, but a responsible adult should be available at the start and end of each day, and contactable throughout. We will need access to the property each morning." },
        { q: "Should I protect my floors?", a: "Yes — we recommend protecting hard floors with hardboard or thick dust sheets in the kitchen and all access routes. We take care in our work but installation involves heavy units and tools." },
        { q: "When should stone worktop templating happen?", a: "Stone worktop templating must happen after base units are installed and levelled, typically on day 2 or 3 of the installation. The stone supplier then returns 5–10 working days later to fit the worktop. Plan your installation programme around this." },
        { q: "What happens to my old kitchen?", a: "Strip-out and disposal of the old kitchen is not included in our standard service but can be arranged. Most clients arrange for a skip or a separate clearance service. Please discuss at your survey." },
      ],
