      answer: "We fit kitchens of all sizes — from compact galley kitchens with 6 units through to large open-plan kitchens with 30+ units. We also fit single rooms, extensions and barn conversions. Our survey confirms feasibility for any layout.",
      takeaways: ["We fit kitchens from 6 units (small galley) to 30+ units (large open-plan)", "Islands, peninsulas, and bi-fold layouts all within our capability", "Extensions and barn conversions are welcome", "Survey confirms feasibility for any unusual layout"],
      body: `<h2>Kitchen Sizes We Install</h2><p>Install My Kitchen installs kitchens of all sizes and configurations. There is no minimum or maximum kitchen size — our service scales from a compact galley kitchen in a flat or terraced house to a large open-plan kitchen-diner in an extension or new build.</p><h2>Small and Compact Kitchens</h2><p>Small kitchens — typically 6–12 units — are often found in flats, starter homes, and Victorian terraced properties. The challenge with small kitchens is often the opposite of what you might expect: compact spaces with limited manoeuvring room for units, restricted wall lengths requiring precise planning, and low headroom in some older properties. We are experienced in fitting kitchens in all of these conditions.</p><h2>Medium Kitchens</h2><p>Medium kitchens of 13–20 units are the most common installation type we carry out. These are typically found in semis and detached properties across Coventry and Warwickshire, often with a single run of units plus an island or peninsula.</p><h2>Large and Open-Plan Kitchens</h2><p>Large kitchens of 21+ units are increasingly common in extended properties and new builds. Open-plan kitchen-diner-living spaces require careful planning of the installation sequence, and often involve more complex appliance configurations with multiple ovens, induction zones, and integrated refrigeration. Our lead fitters have extensive experience with large kitchen installations.</p><h2>Unusual Configurations</h2><p>We also install kitchens in unusual settings including barn conversions (often with exposed stone walls and sloping ceilings), garden rooms, and listed buildings. Each of these presents specific challenges that our surveyor will assess and plan for.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "What is the smallest kitchen you can fit?", a: "We will fit any kitchen regardless of size. We have installed compact galley kitchens with as few as 4–6 units in flats and narrow terraced properties." },
        { q: "Can you fit a kitchen in an extension?", a: "Yes. New extensions often require co-ordination with the builder's programme for first-fix services. Our surveyor will assess the room and advise on the correct installation sequence." },
        { q: "Can you fit a kitchen island?", a: "Yes. Island installation requires careful levelling and is typically one of the more time-intensive elements of a large kitchen installation. It is included in our standard installation service." },
        { q: "Do you fit outdoor kitchens?", a: "Our standard service covers indoor kitchen installation. We do not routinely fit outdoor kitchens, but please enquire if you have a specific project in mind." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "do-you-fit-worktops",
      title: "Do You Fit Worktops?",
      metaDescription: "Yes — Install My Kitchen fits all worktop types including laminate, solid wood, quartz and granite. Learn about each type and how worktop fitting works.",
      answer: "Yes. We fit all worktop types including laminate, solid wood, quartz, granite and compact laminate. Templating for stone worktops is arranged separately — we co-ordinate with your worktop supplier. Laminate worktops can be supplied and fitted directly by us.",
      takeaways: ["We fit all worktop types as part of the kitchen installation", "Laminate worktops: supplied and fitted directly by us", "Stone worktops (quartz, granite): require separate templating by specialist supplier", "Solid wood worktops: supplied and fitted, require sealing"],
      body: `<h2>Worktop Fitting</h2><p>Worktop fitting is included as part of our standard kitchen installation service. The type of worktop affects the installation process, so here is what to expect for each material.</p><h2>Laminate Worktops</h2><p>Laminate is the most common worktop material in the UK, offering a wide range of appearances at an accessible price. Laminate worktops can be supplied directly by Install My Kitchen in a wide range of finishes, or you may supply your own. We cut and fit laminate on site using specialist tools, creating precise cutouts for sinks and hobs and clean joints where worktops meet at corners.</p><h2>Solid Wood Worktops</h2><p>Solid wood (oak, walnut, beech) worktops require careful handling during installation. They must be acclimatised to the room temperature before cutting, and all cut ends and the underside must be sealed with food-safe oil to prevent moisture ingress. We supply and fit solid wood worktops and provide sealing as part of the installation service.</p><h2>Stone Worktops (Quartz, Granite, Dekton)</h2><p>Stone worktops cannot be cut on site — they are templated and cut by a specialist stone fabricator. The process is: base units are installed and levelled first; the stone supplier visits to template (measure precisely); the template is taken to the fabricator who cuts the stone; the stone supplier returns to fit approximately 5–10 working days after templating. We co-ordinate this process with your stone supplier and ensure the base units are ready for templating at the right point in the installation programme.</p><h2>Compact Laminate (Silestone, Dekton)</h2><p>Compact laminate and sintered stone worktops (Silestone, Dekton, Lapitec) are installed using the same specialist supplier process as natural stone. We co-ordinate with your chosen supplier.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "Do you supply worktops?", a: "We supply laminate and solid wood worktops. For stone (quartz, granite, Dekton), you will need a specialist stone supplier. We are happy to recommend local stone suppliers if required." },
        { q: "How long does worktop fitting take?", a: "Laminate worktops typically take 2–4 hours to fit for a standard kitchen. Stone templating is a 30–60 minute visit; stone fitting takes 2–4 hours. Both are included within the overall installation programme." },
        { q: "Can you fit a worktop without fitting the rest of the kitchen?", a: "We primarily install complete kitchens rather than standalone worktop replacements. If you need a worktop replacement only, please enquire and we will advise whether this is within our current capacity." },
        { q: "What happens if the stone worktop doesn't fit?", a: "Stone is templated precisely after units are installed and levelled, so fitting problems are rare. If an issue arises, it is typically resolved between the stone supplier and the fabricator." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "can-you-fit-appliances",
      title: "Can You Fit Appliances?",
      metaDescription: "Yes — Install My Kitchen fits all built-in kitchen appliances. Hardwired appliances need an electrician; plumbed appliances need a plumber. Full guide here.",
      answer: "Yes. We fit all built-in appliances including ovens, hobs, dishwashers, washing machines, extractor fans and fridges. Electrical connection of hardwired appliances (ovens, hobs) requires a qualified electrician, which we recommend you arrange separately.",
      takeaways: ["We fit all integrated kitchen appliances", "Ovens and hobs require an electrician for hardwired connection", "Dishwashers and washing machines require a plumber for water connections", "Co-ordinate your electrician and plumber in advance"],
      body: `<h2>Appliance Fitting</h2><p>Appliance installation is included within our standard kitchen installation service. We fit all types of integrated kitchen appliances — what we do varies by appliance type.</p><h2>Ovens and Hobs</h2><p>Built-in ovens are positioned in their housing units, secured with the manufacturer's fixing brackets, and connected to the electrical supply. The electrical connection of a hardwired oven or hob (a 6mm or 10mm radial circuit) must be made by a Part P qualified electrician — this is a legal requirement. We position and fit the appliance; your electrician makes the connection. The same applies to electric hobs and induction hobs.</p><h2>Extractor Fans and Cooker Hoods</h2><p>Extractor fans and cooker hoods are fitted as part of our standard installation. Ducted extractors require routing of a duct to an external wall or ceiling void — the routing should be discussed and planned at the survey stage. Recirculating extractors require only electrical connection, made by your electrician.</p><h2>Dishwashers and Washing Machines</h2><p>Integrated dishwashers and washing machines are positioned in their housing units and connected with their fascia doors. The plumbing connections — water inlet, waste outlet — are made by your plumber as part of second-fix plumbing.</p><h2>Fridges and Freezers</h2><p>Integrated fridge-freezers and under-counter fridges are positioned and secured within their housing units. Connection to the electrical supply is by plug and socket — no electrician is required for standard refrigeration appliances.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "Can you connect a gas hob?", a: "Gas connections must be made by a Gas Safe registered engineer. We fit the hob into the worktop cutout; your gas engineer makes the gas connection. This is a legal requirement — never connect gas appliances yourself." },
        { q: "Can you fit a range cooker?", a: "Yes — range cookers (freestanding or semi-integrated) are fitted as part of the kitchen installation. Gas range cookers require a Gas Safe engineer for the gas connection." },
        { q: "Do you fit boiling water taps?", a: "Yes — boiling water taps (Quooker, Brita, etc.) are fitted as part of the installation. They require both plumbing connections (made by your plumber) and an electrical connection to a socket under the sink." },
        { q: "What if an appliance doesn't fit the space?", a: "Appliance dimensions are checked against unit dimensions during the pre-installation survey. If a conflict is identified, we advise on the solution before installation day." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "what-happens-during-kitchen-survey",
      title: "What Happens During a Kitchen Installation Survey?",
      metaDescription: "During our survey we check room dimensions, services, levels, walls, access and appliances, then provide a fixed quote. Survey £195, credited back on booking.",
      answer: "During our survey we check your room dimensions against your kitchen plan, assess walls, floors, ceiling height and access routes, confirm service positions, review appliance positions, identify any risks, and provide a fixed installation quote. The survey costs £195, credited back on booking.",
      takeaways: ["Survey takes 45 minutes to 1.5 hours", "We check dimensions, services, levels, walls, access and appliances", "You receive a fixed installation quote following the survey", "The £195 fee is credited back when you confirm your installation date"],
      body: `<h2>What Happens During a Kitchen Survey?</h2><p>Our pre-installation survey is a structured assessment of your home and kitchen plan. Here is exactly what happens from the moment our surveyor arrives.</p><h2>Stage 1 — Room Dimensions</h2><p>Our surveyor measures every dimension of your kitchen using a laser measuring tool — length, width, ceiling height, window and door positions, and any structural features such as chimney breasts, columns, or sloping ceilings. These measurements are compared against your kitchen designer's plan. Any discrepancies are noted and discussed.</p><h2>Stage 2 — Services Assessment</h2><p>The positions of all services are checked and recorded: cold water supply and waste pipe positions for the sink and dishwasher, electrical socket and circuit positions, and gas supply position if applicable. We confirm that services are (or will be, after first fix) in the correct positions for the planned appliance and sink locations.</p><h2>Stage 3 — Room Condition</h2><p>We assess floor levels using a spirit level and laser, wall conditions (plumb, flat, solid), and ceiling height. Unlevel floors, out-of-plumb walls, and hollow areas behind walls are all noted as factors that affect the installation programme and quote.</p><h2>Stage 4 — Access</h2><p>We check that all units — particularly tall larder units, large appliances, and island sections — can physically be brought through your front door, hallway, and into the kitchen. This is more important than it might seem: a 600mm larder unit is approximately 220cm tall and needs a clear route.</p><h2>Stage 5 — The Quote</h2><p>Following the survey (typically the same day or within 24 hours), we provide a fixed installation quote covering all agreed elements of the installation. This quote does not change unless you change the scope of work.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "How long does the survey take?", a: "Between 45 minutes and 1.5 hours, depending on kitchen complexity. Please allow up to 2 hours for a large or complex kitchen." },
        { q: "Do I need my kitchen plan for the survey?", a: "Yes — please have your kitchen plan or designer's drawings available. The more detail you can share, the more accurate the survey. Appliance specifications and measurements are also helpful." },
        { q: "What if my kitchen plan has not been finalised?", a: "We can survey the room without a finalised plan, but the quote will be an estimate rather than a fixed price. We recommend completing the kitchen design before booking the survey." },
        { q: "When do I receive the quote after the survey?", a: "We aim to provide your fixed installation quote within 24 hours of the survey. For complex projects, this may be 48 hours." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "kitchen-installation-warwickshire",
      title: "Kitchen Installation Warwickshire | Install My Kitchen",
      metaDescription: "Install My Kitchen covers all of Warwickshire including Rugby, Leamington Spa, Kenilworth, Warwick and Stratford-upon-Avon. Independent fitting for all retailers.",
      answer: "Install My Kitchen covers all of Warwickshire including Rugby, Nuneaton, Leamington Spa, Kenilworth, Warwick, Stratford-upon-Avon, Southam and surrounding villages. We install kitchens from all major retailers.",
      takeaways: ["Full Warwickshire coverage from our Coventry base", "Rugby, Nuneaton, Leamington Spa, Kenilworth, Warwick all covered", "Independent fitting for Wren, Howdens, Magnet, IKEA and all retailers", "Call 07399 651836 to book your survey"],
      body: `<h2>Kitchen Installation Across Warwickshire</h2><p>Install My Kitchen is based in Coventry and provides kitchen installation services throughout Warwickshire. Our regular coverage area includes all of the following Warwickshire towns and their surrounding villages.</p><h2>Areas We Cover in Warwickshire</h2><ul><li><strong>Rugby:</strong> Rugby town, Clifton upon Dunsmore, Long Lawford, Dunchurch and surrounding villages</li><li><strong>Nuneaton:</strong> Nuneaton, Bedworth, Bulkington, Exhall and surrounding areas</li><li><strong>Leamington Spa:</strong> Royal Leamington Spa, Whitnash, Radford Semele and surrounding villages</li><li><strong>Kenilworth:</strong> Kenilworth town and surrounding villages</li><li><strong>Warwick:</strong> Warwick town, Barford, Bishop's Tachbrook and surrounding villages</li><li><strong>Stratford-upon-Avon:</strong> Stratford and surrounding south Warwickshire villages</li><li><strong>Southam:</strong> Southam town and surrounding villages</li><li><strong>Atherstone:</strong> Atherstone and north Warwickshire</li></ul><h2>Warwickshire Housing and Kitchen Types</h2><p>Warwickshire's housing stock is varied. The county has a high proportion of period properties — Victorian and Edwardian in towns such as Leamington Spa and Kenilworth, older rural properties in villages across the county, and newer executive detached homes in developments around Rugby and Stratford-upon-Avon. We are experienced in working in all of these property types, from cottages with uneven stone walls to new builds with open-plan kitchen extensions.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "Do you cover all of Warwickshire?", a: "We cover the main Warwickshire towns and their surrounding areas. If your location is not listed above, please call 07399 651836 and we will confirm whether we can help." },
        { q: "Is there a travel charge for Warwickshire installations?", a: "There is no additional travel charge for locations within our standard coverage area. All Warwickshire towns listed above are within our standard service area." },
        { q: "Do you install premium kitchens in Warwickshire?", a: "Yes. Warwickshire has a significant market for premium and luxury kitchen brands. We install Mereway, Häcker, Neptune, deVOL and all other premium brands throughout the county." },
        { q: "How quickly can I get a survey in Warwickshire?", a: "Survey appointments in Warwickshire are typically available within 1–2 weeks. Call 07399 651836 to check current availability." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "shaker-kitchen-installation-coventry",
      title: "Shaker Kitchen Installation Coventry",
      metaDescription: "Shaker kitchens are one of the most popular styles in Coventry. Install My Kitchen fits shaker kitchens from all major retailers across Coventry and Warwickshire.",
      answer: "Shaker kitchens are one of the most popular styles in Coventry and Warwickshire. Install My Kitchen installs shaker kitchens from Wren, Howdens, Magnet, IKEA and all major retailers. We handle the full installation including frames, doors, plinths and cornices.",
      takeaways: ["Shaker is the most popular kitchen style in the UK", "We fit shaker kitchens from all major retailers", "Painted shaker requires particular care with door alignment", "Available in all Coventry postcodes and across Warwickshire"],
      body: `<h2>Shaker Kitchen Installation in Coventry</h2><p>The shaker kitchen style — characterised by its recessed panel doors, clean lines, and timeless appearance — is consistently the most popular kitchen style in the UK. In Coventry and Warwickshire, shaker kitchens account for a large proportion of the installations we carry out, across all price points from entry-level vinyl-wrapped shaker doors to painted solid wood in-frame shaker kitchens.</p><h2>Shaker Kitchens by Retailer</h2><p>Almost every major UK kitchen retailer offers a shaker range:</p><ul><li><strong>Wren:</strong> J-Pull and Clerkenwell shaker ranges</li><li><strong>Howdens:</strong> Greenwich, Tewkesbury, and Burford shaker ranges</li><li><strong>Magnet:</strong> Belgravia and Florence shaker ranges</li><li><strong>IKEA:</strong> BODBYN, AXSTAD, and HITTARP shaker-style ranges</li><li><strong>Benchmarx:</strong> Quality shaker ranges through Travis Perkins trade supply</li></ul><p>We are experienced in installing shaker kitchens from all of these retailers and many more. The installation process is consistent across brands — the differences lie in hardware quality, door weight, and the precision required for the finish.</p><h2>Painted Shaker Kitchens</h2><p>Painted shaker kitchens require additional care during installation. Painted doors are heavier than vinyl-wrapped equivalents and more susceptible to showing alignment imperfections. The snagging stage of a painted shaker kitchen installation is more detailed — each door gap is checked for consistency and every hinge adjusted until the finish is uniform. This is a strength of our installation service: we take the time to get the detail right.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "What is the difference between a shaker and an in-frame kitchen?", a: "A shaker kitchen has doors hung on the face of the carcass with a shaker-style recessed panel. An in-frame kitchen has doors hung within a solid timber frame that is part of the carcass structure. In-frame is more expensive and requires more precise installation." },
        { q: "How long does a shaker kitchen take to install?", a: "A standard shaker kitchen takes the same time as any kitchen of equivalent size — 3–10 days depending on size and complexity. A painted in-frame shaker may take slightly longer due to the care required in door adjustment." },
        { q: "Do you fit shaker kitchens from independent designers?", a: "Yes. We install shaker kitchens from independent kitchen designers as well as major retailers. Bespoke and designer kitchens typically require more time and care and are quoted accordingly following survey." },
        { q: "Can you fit cornices and light pelmets on a shaker kitchen?", a: "Yes — cornices, light pelmets, and all finishing trims are included in our standard installation service." },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: "how-to-book-kitchen-installation",
      title: "How to Book Kitchen Installation",
      metaDescription: "Book kitchen installation with Install My Kitchen in 4 steps: survey, quote, deposit, installation date. Survey £195, credited back. Call 07399 651836.",
      answer: "To book a kitchen installation: book a survey (£195, credited back on booking). We visit your home, check the room and plans, then provide a fixed quote. Once you confirm with a deposit, we secure your installation date. Call 07399 651836 or book online.",
      takeaways: ["Step 1: Book a survey — call 07399 651836 or use the online form", "Step 2: Receive your fixed installation quote (within 24 hours)", "Step 3: Confirm with a deposit to secure your installation date", "Step 4: Installation day — we arrive, you get your kitchen"],
      body: `<h2>How to Book Your Kitchen Installation</h2><p>Booking a kitchen installation with Install My Kitchen is a straightforward four-step process designed to ensure your installation is planned properly and your date is secured well in advance.</p><h2>Step 1 — Book Your Survey</h2><p>The first step is to book a pre-installation survey. You can do this by calling us on 07399 651836 (Monday to Saturday, 8am to 6pm) or by completing the online booking form. We will confirm a survey date — typically within 1–2 weeks — at a time that suits you.</p><h2>Step 2 — Your Survey Visit</h2><p>Our surveyor visits your home to assess the room, review your kitchen plan, and confirm all service positions. The survey typically takes 45–90 minutes. The survey fee is £195, payable at the time of booking. Following the survey, you receive a fixed installation quote within 24 hours.</p><h2>Step 3 — Confirm Your Booking</h2><p>If you are happy with the quote, confirm your booking by paying a 30% deposit. This secures your installation date in our diary. We typically book installations 2–4 weeks in advance, though availability varies by season. We recommend booking as early as possible — our schedule fills quickly, particularly in spring and summer.</p><h2>Step 4 — Installation</h2><p>On installation day, our team arrives at the agreed time and begins work. We will have confirmed all pre-installation requirements with you in advance — delivery complete, first-fix trades done, room cleared. The installation proceeds according to the agreed programme, with daily updates. On the final day, we complete a full snagging check and hand over your finished kitchen.</p>`,
      faqs: [
        { q: "How far in advance do I need to book?", a: "We recommend booking as early as possible. Our installation schedule typically runs 3–6 weeks ahead. Popular periods (spring, pre-Christmas) fill faster — book early to secure your preferred date." },
        { q: "Can I book an installation before my kitchen is delivered?", a: "Yes — you can book a survey and confirm a provisional installation date before delivery. We will confirm final arrangements once delivery is scheduled." },
        { q: "What is the deposit amount?", a: "We require a 30% deposit to confirm your installation date. The balance is due on completion of the installation." },
        { q: "Can I cancel or reschedule?", a: "Please give as much notice as possible if you need to cancel or reschedule. Cancellations less than 14 days before the installation date may result in a cancellation fee. Full details are provided with your booking confirmation." },
      ],
    },
  ];

  return questions.map((q, i) => ({
    params: { question: q.slug },
    props: { ...q, index: i },
  }));
}

const { slug, title, metaDescription, answer, takeaways, body, faqs, index } = Astro.props;
const canonical = `https://installmykitchen.co.uk/answers/${slug}/`;

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": faqs.map(f => ({
    "@type": "Question",
    "name": f.q,
    "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": f.a }
  }))
};
---

<Base title={`${title} | Install My Kitchen`} description={metaDescription} canonical={canonical}>
  <script slot="schema" type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

  <Header slot="header" />

  <div class="container py-6">
    <Breadcrumbs items={[{ label: "Questions & Answers", href: "/answers/" }, { label: title, href: canonical }]} />
  </div>

  <section class="section" style="background: var(--bg-light);">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl">
      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-extrabold mb-6 leading-tight" style="color: var(--navy);">{title}</h1>
      <AnswerBlock answer={answer} />
      <div class="mt-6">
        <KeyTakeaway points={takeaways} />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl">
      <div class="prose-content" set:html={body} />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-sm" style="background: var(--bg-light);">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6" style="color: var(--navy);">Related Questions</h2>
      <FAQ items={faqs} schemaId={`faq-${slug}`} />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-sm">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl">
      <InternalLinks
        heading="Explore More"
        links={[
          { label: "Book a survey — £195 credited back", href: "/survey/", description: "Get an accurate fixed quote for your kitchen installation." },
          { label: "More questions answered", href: "/questions/", description: "Browse all kitchen installation questions and answers." },
          { label: "Installation cost guide", href: "/costs/", description: "Full breakdown of kitchen installation costs." },
          { label: "Pindi Sahota — 30 years experience", href: "/pindi-sahota/", description: "Meet your installer." },
          { label: "See completed installations", href: "/projects/", description: "Real kitchens we have fitted across Coventry and Warwickshire." },
          { label: "Installation checklist", href: "/checklist/", description: "Everything you need to do before installation day." },
          { label: "About Install My Kitchen", href: "/about/", description: "Who we are and how we work." },
          { label: "Contact us", href: "/contact/", description: "Call 07399 651836 or send an enquiry." },
        ]}
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTA heading="Ready to Book Your Kitchen Installation?" subtext="Book a survey and get a fixed quote within 24 hours. Survey fee £195 — credited back on booking." primaryLabel="Book a Survey" primaryHref="/survey/" secondaryLabel="Call 07399 651836" secondaryHref="tel:07399651836" dark={true} />

  <Footer slot="footer" />
  <StickyMobileCTA slot="sticky-cta" />
</Base>

<style>
  .prose-content :global(h2) { font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--navy); margin: 2rem 0 0.75rem; }
  .prose-content :global(p) { color: var(--text-soft); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .prose-content :global(ul) { color: var(--text-soft); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; }
  .prose-content :global(li) { margin-bottom: 0.4rem; }
  .prose-content :global(strong) { color: var(--charcoal); font-weight: 600; }
</style>
